June 27, 2018

Travelling Europe by Bike

People kept asking me how I got this crazy idea in the first place to travel Europe by bike. I found it hard to answer. It happened one day when I casually browsed a website that described a man who took a trans-Canada trip by bike, an idea occurred suddenly that I might just as well do what the guy had done. Although I was not very serious about it, I began to collect the information I needed, and bought a sleeping bag, a tent, two panniers, a camping stove, and other necessary equipments. Going to Europe topped the bucket list for my retirement plan since I had never been to Europe. Why did I choose to travel by bike instead of other vehicles? Well, as many cyclists said, traveling by car is too fast, while traveling by foot is too slow.

I arrived at Vienna airport in the very early morning, so I had plenty of time to reassemble my bike. Even though I had read the map in advance, it still took me three hours to get from the airport to Vienna. It was not as easy as I had thought before. For the first time, I stayed in a hostel--a youth hostel located at the suburbs of Vienna--partly because the rent was cheap, and partly because I wanted to have a brand new experience. It was a mixed bedroom with eight single beds, each with a separate locker. The stay there turned out to be quite a pleasure since I could talk with people from different countries. During the stay in Vienna, I visited the Schönbrunn Palace, the National Library, the Opera House, the Hofburg Palace, the City Hall, etc. I enjoyed viewing the buildings of Baroque style and the churches with the towering steeples, gorgeous ceilings, and sacred altars. Having been deeply impressed by the walt “The Blue Danube,” I went to see the famous Danube river. When I was riding my bike along the river, there were some young ladies taking sunbath--naked without a stitch. To avoid being liable to lay myself open to suspicion, I dared not take my camera out. It was a pity that I didn’t wear my sunglasses. The water is clean and you could see the waterweed on the bottom but it was not as beautiful as I had imagined.

I set out for Prague at about five o’clock in order to avoid the traffic jam. Bidding farewell to Vienna, I enjoyed the endless typical European pastoral sceneries and beautiful farmlands on my way to Prague. Although the route was flat, most part of the road didn’t have the shoulders. I was a little worried about the traffic, so I tried to ride on the side of the road as much as I could. To my relief, the drivers seemed to expect to see cyclists and was generous enough to give away ample room for me. If they wanted to overtake a cyclist, they did it via the opposite lane when possible. When I went through a construction area that was about 1,000 meters long, there were many traffic cones on the middle line. Surprisingly, at least 20 more cars just patiently followed behind me until the end of area. Nobody sounded a horn. What unbelievably nice drivers they were!

The Google Map was not always reliable. After I crossed the Danube river, it guided me to the freeway. There was nobody who I could ask for help and I didn’t have a paper map either. I began to feel panic. I walked my bike on the ramp and wanted to make sure whether the bike was allowed on the freeway. A young lady driver honked a horn and waved her hand to tell me that the bike was prohibited to enter the freeway. I felt depressed and sat there for a little while to think what I should do next. Unintentionally I saw a small path that ran parallel to the freeway. I could not help but choose it. The way led me to a small village. When I asked a villager how to get to Prague, I felt funny because I was about 300 kilometers away from there. In order to make sure I was on the right track, I tried to ask whomever I met. Before I passed through the border of Austria and the Czech Republic, the route led me to the freeway again. This almost drove me crazy. I had no choice but to detour to a country road. I had totally got lost. When I saw the road signs written in Czech, I wondered where the customs were. I was afraid that I might miss the customs during my bypass and become an illegal immigrant. On arriving the B&B, I was anxious to ask the receptionist about my doubt. She said there were no customs among EU member countries, so I felt at ease.

When in Prague, I stayed at the Charles University Student Dormitory. In order to earn more money, the school authorities had the dormitory open to travellers during summer time when most students went home. It was a single room. The bedroom was OK; the bus stop was within walking distance; the rent was reasonable. The only problem was the bathroom -- a big bathroom that had more than 20 shower cabinets in it. Adjacent shower cabinets stood face to face, each with door frame but without either a door or a curtain. Both men and women used the same bathroom. It was quite a culture shock for me.

The Charles bridge, and the Praque Castle in the back ground

The entire city of Prague is a world heritage site. Because most of the crowded, narrow streets in the old town were in the walking area, I decided to buy a weekly pass to take the public transportation system instead of riding my bike. When I went to buy a ticket, the officer asked to see my passport. To my surprise, he gave me a senior pass after finding that I was over 65 years old. It means that with the pass, I could take metros, street cars, buses, and funicular railway for free in Prague for the rest of my life. I could even get a discount when I went to see the puppet show. Hurrah for the Czech Republic!

The red roofs mingled with the steeples

The Vltava river meanders through the Prague city. There are many arch bridges across the river. One of the most famous is Charles Bridge which connects the Old Town and the Little Quarter. Although the bridge is now a pedestrian precinct, at one time it could take four carriages abreast. The bridge was full of tourists, street artists, and trinket and craft stalls, with lots of statues on its both sides. To prevent damage caused by wear and tear, many of the statues on the bridge were duplicates, their originals kept in the National Museum. There were some tourist cruises moving to and fro on the river. After crossing the bridge, you will be in the Little Quarter. Walking in this area makes you feel like strolling on a Renaissance street. One of the streets will lead you to the highlight of Prague: Prague Castle. This big splendorous building is now the house of president of the Czech Republic. Many visitors waited to see the changing of the Guard at the front gate of the Castle, which accommodates the president’s office, a cathedral, a chapel, a powder tower, the National Museum, and a garden.

Salzburg is situated at the confluence of the Salzach river and the Saalach river. Both rivers are borders of Germany and Austria. Like Prague, it is listed as one of the UNESCO World Heritage Sites. Salzburg was the birthplace of Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart and the setting for the musical film The Sound of Music. Hohensalzburg Castle perches high on Festungsburg, a small hill in the city of Salzburg offering a panorama view of Salzburg. The architectures here are mainly in Baroque style. You could see churches everywhere. The street musicians here were professional. I heard someone say they were students majoring in music. In order to earn some extra money, they performed as street musicians when they had free time. No wonder many visitors stopped to enjoy their performance. The International Student Dormitory in Salzburg was a sweet home from home. Like Charles University, they opened it to travellers during summer vacation. It was a suite and each room had its own kitchen. Mirabell Palace, a geometrically-arranged garden, was one of the most popular tourists’ attractions in Salzburg. Hellbrunn Palace, located in the outskirts of Salzburg, was, however, not as popular. I went there partly because it was near the dormitory and partly because I got to see the pavilion famous for its appearance in The Sound of Music.

While staying at the shore of Wolfgangsee, I took the railway to the top of the Schafberg mountain. It was a unique experience to ride the steam locomotive up there and enjoy such breathtaking views in all angles. You could see four lakes at the top of the mountain: The Mondsee and the Attersee are to the north, and the Wolfgangsee and the Fuschlsee to the south. The houses were scattered at the foot of the Alps, looking exactly like one of the calendar pictures. Hallstatt is another World Heritage Site in Austria. I used to see the pictures of Hallstatt and now standing right in it, I was deeply fascinated by its stunning landscape of lakes and mountains. What’s even more amazing is an incredible coincidence that followed: I met a young Japanese there who also visited Hallstatt just because of a picture of the Austrian village he saw!

While I was staying at the Chiemsee campground, Germany, the people next to my tent kept me awake all night. It suddenly occurred to me that I had left my home for over one month. I sensed a strong feeling of nostalgia, missing my family and friends desperately. Although I had not finished the original plan for the journey, I decided to return home as soon as possible. I was no traveler after all: A real traveler would not get homesick in such a short time.

Reviewing my whole tour, I don’t think I had prepared well enough for this trip. I should have bought a bike electrical generator and a sim card to be used in Europe. With these two, I would not have got lost all the time. I was so lucky to always have someone help me whenever I was in trouble. I remember that when I stood and looked around at an intersection to find my way to Chiemsee, an elderly couple stopped their car to ask me where I was heading for. After knowing my intended destination, they even offered me a ride to get there. Neither can I forget the time when I went to a grocery store next to the Wolfgangsee campground to buy

a cabbage--the last one on the shelf. When I stood in front of the counter, ready to pay, an elderly woman came out from a room and took my cabbage back and then brought out a better one to me. She thought the first one was not good enough for sale. What an honest lady she was! The people of all three countries I visited -- Czech Republic, Austria, and Germany -- were incredibly friendly to cyclists--and foreigners too. Should I have another chance for traveling abroad, I will definitely visit these countries again.

Hallstatt
